-- ── Cadence Design Systems ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cadence Design Systems (NASDAQ: CDNS) is one of the world's largest electronic design automation (EDA) companies, providing the software, hardware, and IP that semiconductor and systems companies use to design integrated circuits, systems-on-chip, printed circuit boards, and increasingly full electronic systems. Headquartered in San Jose, California, Cadence traces its roots to the 1988 merger of SDA Systems and ECAD, and has since grown into a company with roughly 13,800 employees and multi-billion-dollar annual revenue. Its product portfolio spans digital and custom/analog IC design, verification (including hardware-assisted emulation and prototyping systems), PCB and multi-die packaging design, and, following its expansion into computational software, molecular modeling and simulation tools used by pharmaceutical and life sciences companies. Cadence competes primarily with Synopsys and Siemens EDA (formerly Mentor Graphics) in what is effectively an oligopoly at the center of the global chip industry, meaning nearly every major semiconductor company relies on Cadence, a competitor, or both to bring new chips to market. Because chip design tools are highly specialized, mission-critical, and sold through direct enterprise sales rather than self-serve signup, Cadence does not publish public pricing and instead licenses its software through custom multi-year agreements.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Enterprise licensing sold via direct sales; pricing is not publicly disclosed$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Custom pricing (contact sales); no self-serve or published tiers$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1988, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$10001+$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Jose, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Cadence Design Systems (CDNS) Overview: What It Does and How Its Software Is Licensed$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Cadence Design Systems (NASDAQ: CDNS) makes electronic design automation software for chip and semiconductor design. See what it does, its history, and how licensing works.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Cadence Design Systems is a publicly traded American technology company, listed on NASDAQ under the ticker CDNS, that builds electronic design automation (EDA) software used to design, verify, and manufacture semiconductors and the electronic systems built around them. The company was formed in 1988 through the merger of two earlier EDA companies, SDA Systems and ECAD, and is headquartered in San Jose, California, in the heart of Silicon Valley. Over nearly four decades, Cadence has grown from a niche chip-design tools vendor into one of the two or three companies that essentially every major semiconductor and electronics company depends on, alongside its closest competitor Synopsys and, to a lesser degree, Siemens EDA (the former Mentor Graphics). As of the most recent public filings, Cadence employs roughly 13,800 people worldwide and reports annual revenue in the range of five billion dollars, with a market capitalization that has placed it among the larger software companies on public markets. Cadence's product portfolio is organized around the full lifecycle of chip design. On the digital design and implementation side, its tools handle logic synthesis, place-and-route, and physical design for advanced process nodes. On the custom and analog/mixed-signal side, tools like its Virtuoso platform are used for transistor-level circuit design, which is essential for anything from power management chips to high-speed interfaces. Verification is a major business line in its own right, including functional verification software as well as hardware-assisted emulation and prototyping systems that let engineers test chip designs before committing to expensive silicon fabrication. Cadence also provides printed circuit board (PCB) design and multi-die packaging tools, reflecting the industry's shift toward chiplet-based system design rather than single monolithic dies. In a notable diversification, Cadence has expanded into computational software for life sciences, offering molecular modeling, simulation, and drug discovery tools that apply the company's high-performance computing and simulation expertise outside of semiconductors. Because EDA software is mission-critical, highly specialized infrastructure that directly determines whether a multi-hundred-million-dollar chip design will function correctly, Cadence does not sell through a self-serve website or publish list pricing. Customers, typically semiconductor companies, systems companies, universities, and research labs, license Cadence's tools through direct sales relationships and multi-year enterprise agreements, often bundled with professional services, training, and support. For a directory audience researching Cadence, the most useful framing is that it is not a typical SaaS product with a pricing page, but rather foundational infrastructure software for the global chip industry, comparable in importance to Synopsys, and best evaluated by its product breadth, technology partnerships (including with major foundries like TSMC and Samsung), and its role in enabling the semiconductors that power essentially all modern computing and AI hardware.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '006689e6-24c7-4fff-aebf-57f53db4591e';

