-- ── Caja ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Caja is the default file manager for the MATE desktop environment, a Linux desktop environment that continues the look, feel, and codebase of GNOME 2 after GNOME itself moved to GNOME 3. Caja is a fork of GNOME's Nautilus file manager, forked at the same time MATE itself was forked from GNOME 2 around 2011, and it has been maintained since as a free, open-source component of the MATE project rather than as a standalone commercial product. It handles the everyday tasks users expect from a graphical file manager: browsing local folders, managing files and directories, accessing removable media, connecting to remote filesystems over protocols like SSH, FTP, and WebDAV, and rendering the desktop background and icons on distributions that use MATE as their desktop environment. Note that the name Caja is sometimes confused with the unrelated, now-discontinued Google Caja project, a JavaScript and HTML sandboxing framework for safely embedding third-party web content; Google archived that project in January 2021 and it has no connection to the MATE file manager described here. Caja is preinstalled on MATE-based distributions and spins such as Ubuntu MATE and Linux Mint MATE, and is developed publicly on GitHub under the mate-desktop organization.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free and open-source software; no paid tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2011, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Open-source community project (MATE Desktop team)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$N/A - community-maintained open-source project$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$and dozens of community-translated languages via the MATE project$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Caja File Manager: MATE Desktop's Nautilus-Based File Browser Explained$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Caja is the default file manager for the MATE Linux desktop, forked from GNOME's Nautilus. Learn its features and how it differs from the unrelated, discontinued Google Caja project.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Caja is the default graphical file manager bundled with the MATE desktop environment, a Linux desktop that was forked from GNOME 2 in 2011 after GNOME's own development moved to the very different GNOME 3 interface. When MATE forked GNOME 2's components to keep a traditional desktop metaphor alive, Caja was created at the same time as a fork of GNOME's Nautilus file manager as it existed at that point, and the two projects have since diverged, with Caja retaining and extending features from older Nautilus (such as a split-pane view, tree view, and emblem support) that were later removed from Nautilus itself as GNOME simplified its interface. Caja is free and open-source software, developed publicly on GitHub under the mate-desktop organization, and ships as the standard file manager on MATE-based Linux distributions and desktop spins, most notably Ubuntu MATE and Linux Mint's MATE edition. Functionally, Caja covers the core responsibilities users expect of a desktop file manager: browsing and organizing local files and folders, copying, moving, renaming, and deleting items, managing removable media such as USB drives and optical discs, and connecting to remote filesystems over protocols including SSH (SFTP), FTP, and WebDAV so that remote servers can be browsed like local folders. Beyond file browsing, Caja also plays a role as a core piece of the MATE desktop's shell: it is responsible for rendering the desktop background, placing and arranging desktop icons, and providing the visual entry points users click to open the trash, launch removable media, or access shortcuts to files and applications. It is worth explicitly disambiguating Caja from an unrelated project that shares the same name: Google Caja was a JavaScript and HTML/CSS sandboxing framework built by Google to let websites safely embed third-party content such as widgets and gadgets inside an isolated virtual iframe, based on object-capability security principles. That project was led by Jasvir Nagra with JavaScript sandboxing design work by Google researcher Mark S. Miller, and Google formally archived the Caja security project on January 31, 2021, citing known vulnerabilities and an inability to keep pace with modern web security research, recommending the Closure toolkit as a replacement. Google Caja has no technical or organizational relationship to the MATE Caja file manager described here, and given that Google's project has been discontinued for several years, the actively maintained MATE file manager is almost certainly the software being referenced when the name Caja is used in a current software or Linux desktop context. As with most desktop environment components, Caja is not sold or licensed separately; it is installed automatically as part of a MATE-based Linux distribution and has no independent pricing.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '4bd5937f-e64f-4c25-8c79-12336b88dbbf';

